Here's the approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#4FC3F7</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

### 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.LastOrDefault();
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Themes.LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static AppTheme LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        return Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var t) ? t : AppTheme.Light;
    }
}
```

### 3. Apply the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme());
}
```

### 4. Use `DynamicResource` in your XAML (critical)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello!" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource Accent}" Text="Go" />
</ContentPage>
```

> `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) is what makes the UI update immediately when the dictionary is swapped.

### 5. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
public string[] Themes => Enum.GetNames<AppTheme>();

void OnThemeChanged(object? s, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedIndex < 0) return;
    var chosen = (AppTheme)ThemePicker.SelectedIndex;
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(chosen);
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- One `ResourceDictionary` per theme, same keys in each.
- Swap dictionaries at runtime via `MergedDictionaries`.
- Always bind with `DynamicResource` so changes propagate instantly.
- Persist the user's choice with `Preferences`.
